257
00:21:43,500 --> 00:21:46,540
-I can't stand this guy.
-Oh, Lord!

258
00:21:47,180 --> 00:21:49,580
Yes! Richmond, Virginia.

259
00:21:49,780 --> 00:21:51,060
Smell my ass!

260
00:21:51,260 --> 00:21:53,180
After he smells mine.

261
00:21:53,620 --> 00:21:57,140
That's a shame about your horse
coming in last and all.

262
00:21:57,380 --> 00:22:00,060
But I sure do love
that winning horse of mine, though.

263
00:22:00,220 --> 00:22:02,700
I owe that boy a big kiss
when I see him.

264
00:22:03,300 --> 00:22:07,340
Why don't you give him some of your
cigarettes instead? Lucky fuck!

265
00:22:07,620 --> 00:22:09,100
Hey, Tyrell.

266
00:22:09,460 --> 00:22:11,380
You pull infirmary duty this week?

267
00:22:12,260 --> 00:22:13,780
How's my horse doing anyway?

268
00:22:14,180 --> 00:22:15,220
Dead.

269
00:22:16,100 --> 00:22:18,140
Hadley busted his head up pretty good.

270
00:22:18,380 --> 00:22:20,460
Doc had gone home for the night.

271
00:22:20,940 --> 00:22:23,140
Poor bastard lay there
till this morning.

272
00:22:23,340 --> 00:22:25,700
By then, there wasn't nothing
we could do.

273
00:22:31,740 --> 00:22:32,980
What was his name?

274
00:22:36,220 --> 00:22:37,460
What'd you say?

275
00:22:39,260 --> 00:22:41,540
I was just wondering
if anyone knew his name.

276
00:22:42,220 --> 00:22:44,860
What the fuck do you care, new fish?

277
00:22:45,820 --> 00:22:48,820
Doesn't fucking matter
what his name was. He's dead.

278
00:23:09,980 --> 00:23:11,900
Anybody come at you yet?

279
00:23:13,980 --> 00:23:15,700
Anybody get to you yet?

280
00:23:17,300 --> 00:23:19,740
Hey, we all need friends in here.

281
00:23:20,020 --> 00:23:21,660
I could be a friend to you.

282
00:23:30,460 --> 00:23:31,820
Hard to get.

283
00:23:33,860 --> 00:23:35,260
I like that.

284
00:23:41,940 --> 00:23:45,020
Andy kept pretty much
to himself at first.

285
00:23:45,340 --> 00:23:47,220
I guess he had a lot on his mind...

286
00:23:47,660 --> 00:23:50,380
...trying to adapt
to life on the inside.

287
00:23:51,060 --> 00:23:54,140
Wasn't until a month went by
before he opened his mouth...

288
00:23:54,340 --> 00:23:56,580
...to say more than two words
to somebody.

289
00:23:57,780 --> 00:23:59,220
As it turned out...

290
00:23:59,700 --> 00:24:01,500
...that somebody was me.

291
00:24:09,900 --> 00:24:11,620
I'm Andy Dufresne.

292
00:24:12,820 --> 00:24:14,460
Wife-killing banker.

293
00:24:16,620 --> 00:24:17,860
Why'd you do it?

294
00:24:18,300 --> 00:24:20,260
I didn't, since you ask.

295
00:24:20,860 --> 00:24:22,620
You're going to fit right in.

296
00:24:22,820 --> 00:24:25,380
Everybody in here's innocent.
Didn't you know that?

297
00:24:26,020 --> 00:24:29,100
-What you in here for?
-Didn't do it. Lawyer fucked me.

298
00:24:31,980 --> 00:24:34,460
Rumor has it you're a real cold fish.

299
00:24:34,660 --> 00:24:38,100
You think your shit smells
sweeter than most. Is that right?

300
00:24:38,300 --> 00:24:39,700
What do you think?

301
00:24:40,060 --> 00:24:43,020
To tell you the truth,
I haven't made up my mind.

302
00:24:44,100 --> 00:24:46,780
I understand you're a man
that knows how to get things.

303
00:24:47,740 --> 00:24:50,860
I'm known to locate certain things
from time to time.

304
00:24:51,060 --> 00:24:53,500
I wonder if you might get me
a rock hammer.

305
00:24:54,220 --> 00:24:55,420
A rock hammer.

306
00:24:55,820 --> 00:24:58,340
-What is it and why?
-What do you care?

307
00:24:59,700 --> 00:25:02,260
For a toothbrush, I wouldn't ask.
I'd quote a price.

308
00:25:02,460 --> 00:25:04,780
But a toothbrush
is a non-lethal object, isn't it?

309
00:25:06,300 --> 00:25:07,620
Fair enough.

310
00:25:08,060 --> 00:25:10,580
A rock hammer is about
six or seven inches long.

311
00:25:10,780 --> 00:25:13,020
-Looks like a miniature pickax.
-Pickax?

312
00:25:13,180 --> 00:25:14,340
For rocks.

313
00:25:16,860 --> 00:25:18,020
Quartz?

314
00:25:21,820 --> 00:25:25,140
And some mica, shale...

315
00:25:26,300 --> 00:25:27,540
...limestone.

316
00:25:27,780 --> 00:25:28,860
So?

317
00:25:29,780 --> 00:25:31,540
So I'm a rock hound.

318
00:25:31,900 --> 00:25:34,900
At least I was in my old life.
I'd like to be again.

319
00:25:35,180 --> 00:25:38,180
Or maybe you'd like to sink your toy
into somebody's skull.

320
00:25:39,580 --> 00:25:41,100
No, I have no enemies here.

321
00:25:41,260 --> 00:25:43,460
No? Wait a while.

322
00:25:45,020 --> 00:25:46,580
Word gets around.

323
00:25:47,220 --> 00:25:49,620
The Sisters have taken
quite a liking to you.

324
00:25:50,940 --> 00:25:52,660
Especially Bogs.

325
00:25:53,620 --> 00:25:56,940
Don't suppose it would help if l
told them I'm not homosexual.

326
00:25:57,140 --> 00:25:58,500
Neither are they.

327
00:25:58,700 --> 00:26:01,980
You have to be human first.
They don't qualify.

328
00:26:06,340 --> 00:26:10,540
Bull queers take by force.
That's all they want or understand.

329
00:26:10,740 --> 00:26:14,100
If I were you, I'd grow eyes
in the back of my head.

330
00:26:14,340 --> 00:26:16,980
-Thanks for the advice.
-Well, that's free.

331
00:26:17,300 --> 00:26:19,180
You understand my concern.

332
00:26:19,420 --> 00:26:21,860
If there's trouble,
I won't use the rock hammer.

333
00:26:22,740 --> 00:26:26,660
Then I'd guess you want to escape.
Tunnel under the wall, maybe.

334
00:26:27,500 --> 00:26:29,100
What did I miss?
What's so funny?

335
00:26:29,500 --> 00:26:32,100
You'll understand
when you see the rock hammer.

336
00:26:33,860 --> 00:26:35,980
What's an item like this usually go for?

337
00:26:36,180 --> 00:26:38,580
Seven dollars in any rock-and-gem shop.

338
00:26:39,100 --> 00:26:41,420
My normal markup's 20 percent.

339
00:26:41,620 --> 00:26:43,900
But this is a specialty item.

340
00:26:44,100 --> 00:26:48,380
Risk goes up, price goes up.
Let's make it an even 1 0 bucks.

341
00:26:48,580 --> 00:26:49,860
Ten it is.

342
00:26:51,500 --> 00:26:53,460
Waste of money, if you ask me.

343
00:26:53,740 --> 00:26:54,980
Why's that?

344
00:26:56,300 --> 00:26:59,220
Folks around this joint
love surprise inspections.

345
00:27:00,780 --> 00:27:02,660
They find it, you're going to lose it.

346
00:27:02,820 --> 00:27:04,860
If they catch you, you don't know me.

347
00:27:05,060 --> 00:27:07,220
Mention my name, we never
do business again.

348
00:27:07,660 --> 00:27:10,660
Not for shoelaces or a stick of gum.
Now you got that?

349
00:27:11,460 --> 00:27:12,980
I understand.

350
00:27:14,100 --> 00:27:16,100
Thank you, Mr....

351
00:27:16,340 --> 00:27:17,300
Red.

352
00:27:18,020 --> 00:27:19,260
Name's Red.

353
00:27:20,620 --> 00:27:22,220
Why do they call you that?

354
00:27:25,820 --> 00:27:27,740
Maybe it's because I'm Irish.

355
00:27:35,580 --> 00:27:38,300
I could see why some of the boys
took him for snobby.

356
00:27:39,180 --> 00:27:41,500
He had a quiet way about him...

357
00:27:41,820 --> 00:27:45,780
...a walk and a talk that just
wasn't normal around here.

358
00:27:46,140 --> 00:27:47,580
He strolled...

359
00:27:47,740 --> 00:27:51,780
...like a man in the park without a care
or a worry in the world.

360
00:27:51,980 --> 00:27:56,420
Like he had on an invisible coat
that would shield him from this place.

361
00:27:58,300 --> 00:28:00,460
I think it'd be fair to say...

362
00:28:00,700 --> 00:28:02,820
...I liked Andy from the start.

363
00:28:04,340 --> 00:28:07,980
Let's go! Some of us
got a schedule to keep.

364
00:28:11,140 --> 00:28:13,580
Move it! Come on, move it!

365
00:28:16,060 --> 00:28:18,860
How you doing?
How's the wife treating you?

366
00:28:55,460 --> 00:28:56,860
Andy was right.

367
00:28:57,060 --> 00:28:59,220
I finally got the joke.

368
00:28:59,540 --> 00:29:01,820
It would take a man about 600 years...

369
00:29:02,020 --> 00:29:04,380
...to tunnel under the wall
with one of these.

370
00:29:08,020 --> 00:29:10,340
-Book?
-Not today.

371
00:29:16,140 --> 00:29:17,060
Book?

372
00:29:24,140 --> 00:29:26,180
Delivery for Dufresne.

373
00:29:43,180 --> 00:29:44,700
Here's your book.

374
00:29:49,500 --> 00:29:50,660
Thanks.

375
00:29:56,700 --> 00:30:00,260
We're running low on hexite.
Get on back and fetch us up some.

376
00:30:36,060 --> 00:30:37,500
This will blind you.

377
00:30:37,900 --> 00:30:40,180
Honey, hush.

378
00:30:52,220 --> 00:30:54,100
That's it. You fight!

379
00:30:54,300 --> 00:30:55,740
Better that way.

380
00:31:03,620 --> 00:31:06,580
I wish I could tell you
Andy fought the good fight...

381
00:31:06,780 --> 00:31:08,700
...and the Sisters let him be.

382
00:31:09,220 --> 00:31:10,980
I wish I could tell you that...

383
00:31:11,180 --> 00:31:14,020
...but prison is no fairy-tale world.

384
00:31:15,140 --> 00:31:17,020
He never said who did it.

385
00:31:17,260 --> 00:31:18,780
But we all knew.

386
00:31:23,420 --> 00:31:25,820
Things went on like that for a while.

387
00:31:26,220 --> 00:31:28,620
Prison life consists of routine...

388
00:31:28,860 --> 00:31:30,740
...and then more routine.

389
00:31:33,180 --> 00:31:36,540
Every so often, Andy would show up
with fresh bruises.

390
00:31:37,980 --> 00:31:39,700
The Sisters kept at him.

391
00:31:39,940 --> 00:31:41,900
Sometimes he was able
to fight them off.

392
00:31:42,100 --> 00:31:43,540
Sometimes not.

393
00:31:44,660 --> 00:31:46,740
And that's how it went for Andy.

394
00:31:47,300 --> 00:31:48,980
That was his routine.

395
00:31:49,780 --> 00:31:53,060
I do believe those first two years
were the worst for him.

396
00:31:53,580 --> 00:31:56,780
And I also believe that
if things had gone on that way...

397
00:31:57,100 --> 00:31:59,460
...this place would have
got the best of him.

398
00:32:00,180 --> 00:32:02,860
But then, in the spring of 1949...

399
00:32:03,060 --> 00:32:04,900
...the powers that be decided:

400
00:32:05,100 --> 00:32:08,260
The roof of the license-plate factory
needs resurfacing.

401
00:32:08,460 --> 00:32:11,540
I need a dozen volunteers
for a week's work.

402
00:32:12,220 --> 00:32:13,660
As you know...

403
00:32:14,340 --> 00:32:17,740
...special detail carries with it
special privileges.

404
00:32:17,940 --> 00:32:20,220
It was outdoor detail...

405
00:32:20,620 --> 00:32:24,740
...and May is one damned fine month
to be working outdoors.

406
00:32:24,940 --> 00:32:26,220
Stay in line there.

407
00:32:26,420 --> 00:32:29,460
More than a hundred men
volunteered for the job.

408
00:32:33,540 --> 00:32:36,420
Wallace E. Unger.

409
00:32:36,940 --> 00:32:39,180
Ellis Redding.

410
00:32:39,380 --> 00:32:40,860
Wouldn't you know it?

411
00:32:41,300 --> 00:32:44,500
Me and some fellows I know
were among the names called.

412
00:32:44,660 --> 00:32:46,580
Andrew Dufresne.

413
00:32:46,980 --> 00:32:49,780
It only cost us
a pack of smokes per man.

414
00:32:50,260 --> 00:32:52,660
I made my usual 20 percent, of course.

415
00:32:52,860 --> 00:32:56,140
So this big-shot lawyer
calls me long-distance from Texas.

416
00:32:56,340 --> 00:32:57,820
I say, "Yeah?"

417
00:32:58,100 --> 00:33:01,580
He says, "Sorry to inform you,
but your brother just died."

418
00:33:01,780 --> 00:33:05,540
-I'm sorry to hear that.
-I'm not. He was an asshole.

419
00:33:05,740 --> 00:33:07,860
Ran off years ago.
Figured him for dead.

420
00:33:08,020 --> 00:33:10,220
So this lawyer fellow says to me:

421
00:33:10,420 --> 00:33:14,420
"He died a rich man." Oil wells
and shit. Close to a million bucks.

422
00:33:15,020 --> 00:33:16,820
A million bucks?

423
00:33:17,140 --> 00:33:21,420
-Incredible how lucky some assholes get.
-You going to see any of that?

424
00:33:22,020 --> 00:33:24,660
Thirty-five thousand.
That's what he left me.

425
00:33:24,860 --> 00:33:25,980
Dollars?

426
00:33:26,700 --> 00:33:29,580
That's great! That's like
winning the sweepstakes.

427
00:33:29,900 --> 00:33:30,980
Isn't it?

428
00:33:31,180 --> 00:33:34,020
Dumb shit, what do you think
the government will do to me?

429
00:33:34,180 --> 00:33:36,460
Take a big wet bite
out of my ass is what.

430
00:33:37,220 --> 00:33:38,500
Poor Byron.

431
00:33:39,340 --> 00:33:42,420
Terrible fucking luck, huh?
Crying shame.

432
00:33:42,620 --> 00:33:44,740
Some people really got it awful.

433
00:33:45,020 --> 00:33:46,340
Andy, are you nuts?

434
00:33:46,500 --> 00:33:48,340
Keep your eyes on your mop, man!

435
00:33:48,540 --> 00:33:51,380
You'll pay some tax,
but you'll still end up--

436
00:33:51,580 --> 00:33:54,260
Yeah, maybe enough to buy
a new car, and then what?

437
00:33:54,460 --> 00:33:56,540
I got to pay tax on the car. Repair...

438
00:33:56,740 --> 00:34:00,380
...maintenance, kids pestering you
to take them for a ride all the time.

439
00:34:00,580 --> 00:34:04,100
Then if you figure your tax wrong,
you pay out of your own pocket.

440
00:34:04,260 --> 00:34:06,300
I tell you! Uncle Sam!

441
00:34:06,580 --> 00:34:10,380
He puts his hand in your shirt
and squeezes your tit till it's purple.

442
00:34:12,940 --> 00:34:15,020
-Getting himself killed.
-Keep tarring.

443
00:34:15,260 --> 00:34:17,660
Some brother.
Shit!

444
00:34:22,380 --> 00:34:23,740
Mr. Hadley...

445
00:34:24,580 --> 00:34:25,860
...do you trust your wife?

446
00:34:27,460 --> 00:34:28,860
Oh, that's funny.

447
00:34:29,380 --> 00:34:31,860
You'll look funnier
sucking my dick with no teeth.

448
00:34:32,100 --> 00:34:35,260
What I mean is, do you think
she'd go behind your back?

449
00:34:36,380 --> 00:34:39,620
Step aside, Mert. This fucker's
having himself an accident.

450
00:34:39,820 --> 00:34:40,820
He'll push him off!

451
00:34:41,060 --> 00:34:42,820
If you trust her, you can keep...

452
00:34:43,020 --> 00:34:44,380
...that 35,000.

453
00:34:45,100 --> 00:34:47,460
-What did you say?
-Thirty-five thousand.

454
00:34:48,260 --> 00:34:49,260
All of it.

455
00:34:49,460 --> 00:34:52,420
-Every penny.
-You better start making sense.

456
00:34:52,620 --> 00:34:54,820
If you want to keep it,
give it to your wife.

457
00:34:55,020 --> 00:34:58,780
The IRS allows a one-time-only gift
to your spouse for up to $60,000.

458
00:34:58,980 --> 00:35:01,260
-Bullshit. Tax-free?
-Tax-free.

459
00:35:01,420 --> 00:35:03,300
IRS can't touch one cent.

460
00:35:03,700 --> 00:35:06,060
You're that smart banker
that killed his wife.

461
00:35:06,300 --> 00:35:09,540
Why should I believe you?
So I can end up in here with you?

462
00:35:09,740 --> 00:35:12,460
It's legal. Ask the IRS.
They'll say the same thing.

463
00:35:12,620 --> 00:35:16,540
I feel stupid telling you this.
I'm sure you would have investigated.

464
00:35:16,740 --> 00:35:20,220
I don't need you to tell me
where the bear shit in the buckwheat.

465
00:35:20,460 --> 00:35:23,740
Of course not. But you do need
someone to set it up for you.

466
00:35:23,900 --> 00:35:25,420
That'll cost you. A lawyer.

467
00:35:25,620 --> 00:35:27,740
A bunch of ball-washing bastards!

468
00:35:28,220 --> 00:35:31,540
I suppose I could set it up for you.
That would save you some money.

469
00:35:31,740 --> 00:35:33,740
You get the forms, I'll prepare them...

470
00:35:33,980 --> 00:35:35,620
...nearly free of charge.

471
00:35:36,820 --> 00:35:39,940
I'd only ask three beers apiece
for each of my coworkers.

472
00:35:40,900 --> 00:35:42,380
"Coworkers." That's rich!

473
00:35:43,180 --> 00:35:45,580
A man working outdoors
feels more like a man...

474
00:35:45,780 --> 00:35:49,100
...if he can have a bottle of suds.
That's only my opinion...

475
00:35:49,540 --> 00:35:50,500
...sir.

476
00:35:54,260 --> 00:35:56,140
What are you jimmies staring at?

477
00:35:56,340 --> 00:35:57,820
Let's go! Work!

478
00:36:06,940 --> 00:36:08,820
And that's how it came to pass...

479
00:36:09,020 --> 00:36:11,540
...that on the second-to-last
day of the job...

480
00:36:11,780 --> 00:36:16,180
...the convict crew that tarred
the factory roof in the spring of '49...

481
00:36:16,340 --> 00:36:19,340
...wound up sitting in a row
at 10:00 in the morning...

482
00:36:19,540 --> 00:36:24,780
...drinking icy-cold beer,
courtesy of the hardest screw...

483
00:36:24,980 --> 00:36:28,140
...that ever walked a turn
at Shawshank State Prison.

484
00:36:28,340 --> 00:36:30,660
Drink up while it's cold, ladies.

485
00:36:31,700 --> 00:36:36,060
The colossal prick even managed
to sound magnanimous.

486
00:36:37,180 --> 00:36:41,460
We sat and drank with the sun
on our shoulders and felt like free men.

487
00:36:41,820 --> 00:36:45,140
We could have been tarring
the roof of one of our own houses.

488
00:36:45,300 --> 00:36:48,060
We were the lords of all creation.

489
00:36:48,580 --> 00:36:50,100
As for Andy...

490
00:36:50,340 --> 00:36:52,820
...he spent that break
hunkered in the shade...

491
00:36:53,060 --> 00:36:55,460
...a strange little smile on his face...

492
00:36:55,660 --> 00:36:57,780
...watching us drink his beer.

493
00:37:05,580 --> 00:37:06,860
Want a cold one?

494
00:37:07,540 --> 00:37:10,340
No, thanks. I gave up drinking.

495
00:37:14,140 --> 00:37:17,100
You could argue he done it
to curry favor with the guards.

496
00:37:17,780 --> 00:37:21,420
Or maybe make a few friends
among us cons.

497
00:37:22,100 --> 00:37:23,140
Me?

498
00:37:23,340 --> 00:37:26,020
I think he did it
just to feel normal again...

499
00:37:26,460 --> 00:37:28,540
...if only for a short while.

500
00:37:31,140 --> 00:37:32,140
King me.

501
00:37:33,940 --> 00:37:36,460
-Chess. Now there's a game of kings.
-What?

502
00:37:36,700 --> 00:37:38,340
Civilized. Strategic.

503
00:37:38,980 --> 00:37:41,860
And a total fucking mystery.
I hate it.

504
00:37:42,100 --> 00:37:43,820
Let me teach you someday.

505
00:37:45,300 --> 00:37:46,220
Sure.

506
00:37:46,700 --> 00:37:48,340
We could get a board together.

507
00:37:48,580 --> 00:37:51,500
You're talking to the right man.
I can get things, right?

508
00:37:51,740 --> 00:37:55,540
We might do business on a board,
and I'll carve the pieces myself.

509
00:37:55,740 --> 00:37:58,900
One side in alabaster, one in soapstone.
What do you think?

510
00:37:59,460 --> 00:38:00,820
I think it'll take years.

511
00:38:01,020 --> 00:38:03,460
Years I got.
What I don't have are the rocks.

512
00:38:03,660 --> 00:38:05,540
Pickings are pretty slim in the yard.

513
00:38:05,740 --> 00:38:07,500
Pebbles, mostly.

514
00:38:11,620 --> 00:38:14,300
We're getting to be
kind of friends, aren't we?

515
00:38:15,180 --> 00:38:16,660
Yeah, I guess.

516
00:38:17,260 --> 00:38:18,740
Can I ask you something?

517
00:38:20,140 --> 00:38:21,540
Why'd you do it?

518
00:38:22,700 --> 00:38:24,220
I'm innocent, Red.

519
00:38:24,420 --> 00:38:26,380
Just like everybody else here.

520
00:38:30,540 --> 00:38:32,020
What are you in for?

521
00:38:34,620 --> 00:38:36,700
Murder. Same as you.

522
00:38:36,900 --> 00:38:38,020
Innocent?

523
00:38:40,580 --> 00:38:42,900
Only guilty man in Shawshank.

524
00:39:39,820 --> 00:39:41,260
Where's the canary?

525
00:39:41,420 --> 00:39:42,700
How did you know?

526
00:39:42,900 --> 00:39:45,060
-How did I know what?
-So you don't know.

527
00:39:45,260 --> 00:39:46,380
Come.

528
00:39:48,820 --> 00:39:50,780
This is where the canary is.

529
00:39:53,380 --> 00:39:56,580
Quite a surprise to hear
a woman singing in my house, eh?

530
00:39:59,940 --> 00:40:01,260
That's quite a...

531
00:40:02,180 --> 00:40:03,780
...surprise.

532
00:40:07,900 --> 00:40:09,260
Wait, wait.

533
00:40:09,740 --> 00:40:11,220
Here she comes.

534
00:40:11,460 --> 00:40:14,180
I like this part when she
does that shit with her hair.

535
00:40:14,380 --> 00:40:17,020
I know. I've seen it
three times this month.

536
00:40:17,220 --> 00:40:19,020
Gilda, are you decent?

537
00:40:19,980 --> 00:40:21,060
Me?

538
00:40:23,660 --> 00:40:25,340
God, I love it.

539
00:40:30,340 --> 00:40:33,180
I understand you're a man
that knows how to get things.

540
00:40:34,180 --> 00:40:37,740
I'm known to locate certain things
from time to time. What do you want?

541
00:40:37,940 --> 00:40:39,980
-Rita Hayworth.
-What?

542
00:40:40,540 --> 00:40:41,860
Can you get her?

543
00:40:43,180 --> 00:40:46,420
So this is Johnny Farrel.
I've heard a lot about you.

544
00:40:47,620 --> 00:40:49,820
-Take a few weeks.
-Weeks?

545
00:40:50,020 --> 00:40:54,260
I don't have her stuffed down the front
of my pants right now, sorry to say.

546
00:40:54,780 --> 00:40:56,060
But I'll get her.

547
00:40:56,260 --> 00:40:57,540
Relax.

548
00:40:59,300 --> 00:41:00,580
Thanks.

549
00:41:20,340 --> 00:41:22,020
-Get out!
-I got to change reels!

550
00:41:22,260 --> 00:41:24,140
I said fuck off!

551
00:41:30,020 --> 00:41:31,340
Ain't you going to scream?

552
00:41:32,660 --> 00:41:34,420
Let's get this over with.

553
00:41:39,340 --> 00:41:41,220
He broke my fucking nose!

554
00:41:50,180 --> 00:41:51,380
Now...

555
00:41:51,780 --> 00:41:53,900
