556
00:41:54,140 --> 00:41:56,780
...and you'll swallow
what I give you to swallow.

557
00:41:57,900 --> 00:42:00,380
Then you'll swallow Rooster's.
You broke his nose.

558
00:42:00,580 --> 00:42:02,620
He ought to have
something to show for it.

559
00:42:02,780 --> 00:42:04,620
You put it in my mouth,
you lose it.

560
00:42:04,780 --> 00:42:07,300
No, you don't understand.

561
00:42:07,620 --> 00:42:10,500
Do that and I'll put all eight inches
of this in your ear.

562
00:42:10,700 --> 00:42:14,020
All right, but you should know
that sudden, serious brain injury...

563
00:42:14,220 --> 00:42:16,100
...causes the victim to bite down hard.

564
00:42:16,300 --> 00:42:19,620
In fact, I hear the bite reflex
is so strong...

565
00:42:20,420 --> 00:42:22,780
...they have to pry
the victim's jaws open...

566
00:42:22,980 --> 00:42:24,300
...with a crowbar.

567
00:42:27,100 --> 00:42:28,580
Where do you get this shit?

568
00:42:28,820 --> 00:42:30,140
I read it.

569
00:42:31,500 --> 00:42:34,020
You know how to read,
you ignorant fuck?

570
00:42:35,620 --> 00:42:36,700
Honey!

571
00:42:38,540 --> 00:42:40,220
You shouldn't!

572
00:42:42,780 --> 00:42:45,580
Bogs didn't put anything
in Andy's mouth.

573
00:42:45,820 --> 00:42:47,780
And neither did his friends.

574
00:42:48,220 --> 00:42:51,900
What they did do is beat him
within an inch of his life.

575
00:42:52,540 --> 00:42:54,940
Andy spent a month in the infirmary.

576
00:42:55,700 --> 00:42:58,100
Bogs spent a week in the hole.

577
00:43:02,020 --> 00:43:03,540
Time's up, Bogs.

578
00:43:07,180 --> 00:43:08,740
It's your world, boss.

579
00:43:11,900 --> 00:43:14,580
Return to your cellblocks
for evening count.

580
00:43:14,780 --> 00:43:17,340
All prisoners report for lock down.

581
00:43:31,660 --> 00:43:32,660
What?

582
00:43:44,780 --> 00:43:47,180
-Where's he going?
-Grab his ankles.

583
00:43:52,780 --> 00:43:53,980
Help!

584
00:43:57,500 --> 00:43:59,980
Two things never happened again
after that.

585
00:44:00,260 --> 00:44:03,260
The Sisters never
laid a finger on Andy again.

586
00:44:04,060 --> 00:44:06,420
And Bogs would never walk again.

587
00:44:07,580 --> 00:44:10,940
They transferred him
to a minimum-security hospital upstate.

588
00:44:11,100 --> 00:44:13,820
To my knowledge, he lived out
the rest of his days...

589
00:44:13,980 --> 00:44:15,740
...drinking his food through a straw.

590
00:44:16,700 --> 00:44:20,620
Andy could use a nice welcome back
when he gets out of the infirmary.

591
00:44:22,300 --> 00:44:23,820
Sounds good to us.

592
00:44:24,060 --> 00:44:26,460
I figure we owe him that much
for the beer.

593
00:44:27,140 --> 00:44:29,340
The man likes to play chess.

594
00:44:29,820 --> 00:44:31,660
Let's get him some rocks.

595
00:45:02,940 --> 00:45:04,140
Guys!

596
00:45:04,860 --> 00:45:05,860
I got one.

597
00:45:06,100 --> 00:45:07,500
I got one. Look!

598
00:45:09,340 --> 00:45:13,220
Heywood, that isn't soapstone!
And it ain't alabaster either.

599
00:45:13,460 --> 00:45:15,260
What are you, a fucking geologist?

600
00:45:15,460 --> 00:45:17,100
He's right. It ain't.

601
00:45:17,300 --> 00:45:20,100
-What the hell is it then?
-It's a horse apple.

602
00:45:21,020 --> 00:45:23,300
-Bullshit!
-No, horseshit.

603
00:45:23,500 --> 00:45:24,940
Petrified.

604
00:45:33,540 --> 00:45:34,700
Damn!

605
00:45:35,020 --> 00:45:39,100
Despite a few hitches,
the boys came through in fine style.

606
00:45:39,260 --> 00:45:41,140
And by the weekend
he was due back...

607
00:45:41,380 --> 00:45:44,900
...we had enough rocks saved up
to keep him busy till rapture.

608
00:45:45,700 --> 00:45:48,140
Also got a big shipment in that week.

609
00:45:48,380 --> 00:45:49,460
Cigarettes...

610
00:45:49,660 --> 00:45:50,620
...chewing gum...

611
00:45:50,860 --> 00:45:52,220
...sipping whisky...

612
00:45:52,420 --> 00:45:55,700
...playing cards with naked ladies
on them. You name it.

613
00:45:55,900 --> 00:45:58,540
And of course, the most important item:

614
00:46:00,340 --> 00:46:02,300
Rita Hayworth herself.

615
00:46:37,900 --> 00:46:40,060
Heads up.
They're tossing cells.

616
00:46:40,260 --> 00:46:42,820
Heads up.
They're tossing cells!

617
00:46:44,380 --> 00:46:45,820
119.

618
00:46:47,580 --> 00:46:49,180
123.

619
00:46:59,180 --> 00:46:59,980
On your feet.

620
00:47:02,500 --> 00:47:03,940
Face the wall.

621
00:47:36,700 --> 00:47:38,540
Turn around and face the warden.

622
00:47:44,860 --> 00:47:46,820
Pleased to see you reading this.

623
00:47:48,140 --> 00:47:49,980
Any favorite passages?

624
00:47:50,820 --> 00:47:53,060
"Watch ye, therefore,
for ye know not...

625
00:47:53,260 --> 00:47:55,420
...when the master
of the house cometh."

626
00:47:56,500 --> 00:47:58,580
Mark 1 3:35.

627
00:47:59,300 --> 00:48:01,100
I've always liked that one.

628
00:48:01,980 --> 00:48:03,580
But I prefer...

629
00:48:04,020 --> 00:48:05,820
..."l am the light of the world.

630
00:48:06,260 --> 00:48:09,420
Ye that followeth me
shall have the light of life."

631
00:48:09,620 --> 00:48:12,140
John, chapter 8, verse 1 2.

632
00:48:12,420 --> 00:48:14,380
I hear you're good with numbers.

633
00:48:14,580 --> 00:48:15,500
How nice.

634
00:48:16,700 --> 00:48:18,540
Man should have a skill.

635
00:48:21,020 --> 00:48:21,980
Explain this.

636
00:48:23,100 --> 00:48:26,980
It's called a rock blanket.
It's for shaping and polishing rocks.

637
00:48:27,420 --> 00:48:29,260
A little hobby of mine.

638
00:48:39,700 --> 00:48:41,060
It's pretty clean.

639
00:48:41,300 --> 00:48:44,300
Some contraband here,
but nothing to get in a twist over.

640
00:48:48,420 --> 00:48:50,340
I can't say I approve of this.

641
00:48:51,940 --> 00:48:53,340
But I suppose...

642
00:48:55,340 --> 00:48:57,220
...exceptions can be made.

643
00:49:07,180 --> 00:49:08,460
Lock them up!

644
00:49:11,260 --> 00:49:12,740
I almost forgot.

645
00:49:13,180 --> 00:49:15,260
I'd hate to deprive you of this.

646
00:49:15,980 --> 00:49:17,820
Salvation lies within.

647
00:49:18,020 --> 00:49:19,060
Yes, sir.

648
00:49:27,220 --> 00:49:29,660
Tossing cells was just an excuse.

649
00:49:30,140 --> 00:49:31,340
Truth is...

650
00:49:31,500 --> 00:49:33,900
...Norton wanted to size Andy up.

651
00:49:47,020 --> 00:49:49,220
My wife made that in church group.

652
00:49:51,820 --> 00:49:53,020
Very nice, sir.

653
00:49:54,580 --> 00:49:55,940
You enjoy working the laundry?

654
00:49:57,580 --> 00:49:59,180
No, sir. Not especially.

655
00:49:59,500 --> 00:50:01,860
Perhaps we can find something more...

656
00:50:02,140 --> 00:50:04,420
...befitting a man of your education.

657
00:50:12,180 --> 00:50:13,620
Hey, Jake.
Where's Brooks?

658
00:50:15,380 --> 00:50:18,060
I thought I heard you out here.

659
00:50:18,700 --> 00:50:20,180
I've been reassigned to you.

660
00:50:20,460 --> 00:50:22,700
I know, they told me.

661
00:50:23,500 --> 00:50:25,460
Ain't that a kick in the head?

662
00:50:25,700 --> 00:50:27,860
Well, I'll give you the dime tour.

663
00:50:28,060 --> 00:50:29,180
Come on.

664
00:50:30,500 --> 00:50:32,220
Well, here she is.

665
00:50:32,380 --> 00:50:34,260
The Shawshank Prison Library.

666
00:50:34,940 --> 00:50:36,860
National Geographics...

667
00:50:37,740 --> 00:50:40,420
... Reader's Digest condensed books...

668
00:50:40,620 --> 00:50:42,140
...and Louis L'Amour.

669
00:50:42,660 --> 00:50:44,420
Look magazine.

670
00:50:44,780 --> 00:50:47,020
Erle Stanley Gardners.

671
00:50:47,260 --> 00:50:50,580
Every evening I load up the cart
and make my rounds.

672
00:50:50,780 --> 00:50:53,340
I enter the names
on this clipboard here.

673
00:50:53,820 --> 00:50:56,460
Easy, peasy, Japanese-y.

674
00:50:57,140 --> 00:50:59,940
-Any questions?
-How long have you been librarian?

675
00:51:01,100 --> 00:51:04,980
I come here in '05,
and they made me librarian in 1 9 1 2.

676
00:51:06,180 --> 00:51:08,260
And have you ever had an assistant?

677
00:51:08,540 --> 00:51:10,820
No. Not much to it, really.

678
00:51:11,580 --> 00:51:12,740
Why me? Why now?

679
00:51:13,180 --> 00:51:14,420
I don't know.

680
00:51:14,620 --> 00:51:17,500
But it'd be nice to have
some company down here.

681
00:51:28,340 --> 00:51:30,500
That's him.
That's the one.

682
00:51:37,820 --> 00:51:38,940
I'm Dekins.

683
00:51:39,380 --> 00:51:40,900
I was thinking...

684
00:51:41,540 --> 00:51:45,300
...about setting up some kind of
trust fund for my kids' educations.

685
00:51:49,020 --> 00:51:50,420
I see.

686
00:51:55,340 --> 00:51:58,180
Why don't we have a seat
and talk it over.

687
00:52:01,220 --> 00:52:04,060
Do you have a piece of paper
and a pencil?

688
00:52:14,980 --> 00:52:16,180
Thanks.

689
00:52:16,860 --> 00:52:17,900
So....

690
00:52:19,580 --> 00:52:21,220
Mister Dekins....

691
00:52:22,020 --> 00:52:24,060
And then Andy says, "Mr. Dekins...

692
00:52:24,260 --> 00:52:27,140
...do you want your sons
to go to Harvard or Yale?"

693
00:52:27,340 --> 00:52:28,340
He didn't say that!

694
00:52:28,660 --> 00:52:31,060
As God as my witness!

695
00:52:31,300 --> 00:52:33,020
Dekins blinked for a second...

696
00:52:33,180 --> 00:52:36,180
...then he laughed
and actually shook Andy's hand.

697
00:52:36,620 --> 00:52:38,780
-My ass!
-Shook his hand.

698
00:52:38,980 --> 00:52:41,780
I tell you, I near soiled myself!

699
00:52:41,980 --> 00:52:46,100
All he needed was a suit and tie
and a jiggly hula gal on his desk...

700
00:52:46,260 --> 00:52:48,780
...he'd have been
"Mr. Dufresne," if you please.

701
00:52:48,980 --> 00:52:50,540
Making a few friends?

702
00:52:51,780 --> 00:52:53,380
I wouldn't say "friends."

703
00:52:53,580 --> 00:52:57,260
I'm a convicted murderer
who provides sound financial planning.

704
00:52:57,420 --> 00:52:59,660
It's a wonderful pet to have.

705
00:52:59,860 --> 00:53:01,580
Got you out of the laundry, though.

706
00:53:02,100 --> 00:53:03,940
It might do more than that.

707
00:53:04,140 --> 00:53:06,780
How about expanding the library.
Get some new books.

708
00:53:06,940 --> 00:53:09,460
If you ask for something,
ask for a pool table.

709
00:53:11,060 --> 00:53:13,940
How do you expect to do that?
I mean...

710
00:53:14,140 --> 00:53:17,020
...get new books in here,
"Mr. Dufresne, if you please."

711
00:53:17,420 --> 00:53:19,420
I'll ask the warden for funds.

712
00:53:20,260 --> 00:53:24,340
Six wardens have been through here
in my tenure, and I've learned...

713
00:53:24,580 --> 00:53:26,780
...one immutable, universal truth:

714
00:53:27,020 --> 00:53:28,340
Not one born whose asshole...

715
00:53:28,540 --> 00:53:33,260
...wouldn't pucker up tighter than
a snare drum when you ask for funds.

716
00:53:34,100 --> 00:53:36,860
-The budget's stretched thin as it is.
-I see.

717
00:53:37,060 --> 00:53:40,380
Maybe I could write the state senate
and request funds from them.

718
00:53:40,540 --> 00:53:44,500
They have only three ways to spend
the taxpayers' money for prisons:

719
00:53:44,700 --> 00:53:47,060
More walls, more bars, more guards.

720
00:53:47,220 --> 00:53:49,780
I'd like to try, with permission.
A letter a week.

721
00:53:49,980 --> 00:53:52,620
-They can't ignore me forever.
-Sure can.

722
00:53:52,860 --> 00:53:55,420
But you write your letters
if it makes you happy.

723
00:53:55,700 --> 00:53:58,220
I'll even mail them for you.
How's that?

724
00:53:59,820 --> 00:54:02,500
So Andy started writing
a letter a week...

725
00:54:02,700 --> 00:54:04,220
...just like he said.

726
00:54:08,220 --> 00:54:10,740
And like Norton said...

727
00:54:10,940 --> 00:54:12,340
...Andy got no answers.

728
00:54:20,220 --> 00:54:24,940
The following April, he did tax returns
for half the guards at Shawshank.

729
00:54:26,220 --> 00:54:28,380
Year after that, he did them all...

730
00:54:28,620 --> 00:54:30,460
...including the warden's.

731
00:54:32,100 --> 00:54:35,460
Year after that, they
rescheduled the intramural season...

732
00:54:35,660 --> 00:54:37,980
...to coincide with tax season.

733
00:54:39,500 --> 00:54:43,780
The guards on the opposing teams
all remembered to bring their W-2s.

734
00:54:43,980 --> 00:54:45,220
So Moresby Prison...

735
00:54:45,420 --> 00:54:47,620
...issued you a gun,
but you paid for it.

736
00:54:47,860 --> 00:54:49,460
Right. The holster too.

737
00:54:49,660 --> 00:54:52,020
That's tax-deductible.
You can write that off.

738
00:54:52,220 --> 00:54:55,140
Yes, sir!
Andy was a regular cottage industry.

739
00:54:55,820 --> 00:55:00,100
In fact, it got so busy at tax time,
he was allowed a staff.

740
00:55:00,380 --> 00:55:02,780
Could you hand me
a stack of 1 040s?

741
00:55:02,940 --> 00:55:07,580
Got me out of the wood shop a month out
of the year, and that was fine by me.

742
00:55:08,740 --> 00:55:11,780
And still, he kept
sending those letters.

743
00:55:18,300 --> 00:55:19,300
It's Brooks.

744
00:55:20,380 --> 00:55:21,780
Watch the door.

745
00:55:22,060 --> 00:55:23,340
Please, Brooks.

746
00:55:23,580 --> 00:55:25,340
-Calm the fuck down.
-Stay back!

747
00:55:25,700 --> 00:55:28,220
-Stay back, goddamn it!
-What's going on?

748
00:55:28,420 --> 00:55:30,900
One second he's fine,
then out come the knives.

749
00:55:31,100 --> 00:55:32,860
We can talk about this, right?

750
00:55:33,060 --> 00:55:36,660
There's nothing to talk about.
I'll cut his fucking throat.

751
00:55:36,900 --> 00:55:38,580
What's he done to you?

752
00:55:38,780 --> 00:55:40,380
It's what they done!

753
00:55:40,860 --> 00:55:42,100
I got no choice.

754
00:55:42,500 --> 00:55:44,740
You won't hurt Heywood.
We all know that.

755
00:55:44,940 --> 00:55:47,300
-Right, Heywood?
-Sure.

756
00:55:47,540 --> 00:55:50,700
He's a friend of yours,
and Brooks is a reasonable man.

757
00:55:50,980 --> 00:55:52,020
Right, guys?

758
00:55:52,940 --> 00:55:55,340
So put the knife down.
Look at me.

759
00:55:55,580 --> 00:55:57,740
Put the knife down.

760
00:55:59,580 --> 00:56:01,580
Look at his neck, for God's sake.

761
00:56:02,300 --> 00:56:04,540
Look at his neck. He's bleeding.

762
00:56:05,420 --> 00:56:06,820
It's the only way...

763
00:56:07,020 --> 00:56:08,980
...they'd let me stay.

764
00:56:09,260 --> 00:56:11,500
This is crazy.
You don't want to do this.

765
00:56:11,740 --> 00:56:13,740
Put it, put it down.

766
00:56:22,140 --> 00:56:23,540
Take it easy.

767
00:56:24,220 --> 00:56:25,700
You'll be all right.

768
00:56:26,700 --> 00:56:28,220
Him? What about me?

769
00:56:28,420 --> 00:56:30,740
Crazy old fool damn near cut my throat!

770
00:56:30,940 --> 00:56:32,780
You've had worse from shaving.

771
00:56:32,940 --> 00:56:34,940
What did you do to set him off?

772
00:56:35,180 --> 00:56:37,300
Nothing.
I come in here to say farewell.

773
00:56:37,900 --> 00:56:40,420
Ain't you heard?
His parole's come through.

774
00:56:42,700 --> 00:56:45,380
I just don't understand
what happened in there.

775
00:56:45,580 --> 00:56:48,260
Old man's crazy as a rat
in a tin shithouse.

776
00:56:48,460 --> 00:56:50,260
That's enough out of you.

777
00:56:50,460 --> 00:56:53,100
-Heard he had you shitting your pants.
-Fuck you.

778
00:56:53,340 --> 00:56:54,460
Knock it off.

779
00:56:55,420 --> 00:56:56,780
Brooks ain't no bug.

780
00:57:00,460 --> 00:57:02,180
He's just institutionalized.

781
00:57:03,500 --> 00:57:05,340
"Institutionalized," my ass.

782
00:57:05,540 --> 00:57:09,340
The man's been in here 50 years,
Heywood, 50 years!

783
00:57:09,540 --> 00:57:11,220
This is all he knows.

784
00:57:11,420 --> 00:57:13,620
In here, he's an important man...

785
00:57:13,820 --> 00:57:14,900
...an educated man.

786
00:57:15,660 --> 00:57:17,500
Outside, he's nothing.

787
00:57:18,340 --> 00:57:21,660
Just a used-up con
with arthritis in both hands.

788
00:57:21,900 --> 00:57:24,740
Probably couldn't get a library card
if he tried.

789
00:57:25,020 --> 00:57:26,700
You know what I'm trying to say?

790
00:57:26,940 --> 00:57:29,740
I do believe
you're talking out of your ass.

791
00:57:30,940 --> 00:57:33,060
You believe whatever you want.

792
00:57:33,700 --> 00:57:35,980
But I tell you these walls are funny.

793
00:57:37,500 --> 00:57:39,100
First you hate them.

794
00:57:40,860 --> 00:57:42,700
Then you get used to them.

795
00:57:44,540 --> 00:57:46,460
Enough time passes...

796
00:57:47,100 --> 00:57:49,020
...you get so you depend on them.

797
00:57:49,980 --> 00:57:52,100
That's "institutionalized."

798
00:57:52,300 --> 00:57:53,500
Shit.

799
00:57:53,740 --> 00:57:56,380
-I could never get like that.
-Oh, yeah?

800
00:57:57,180 --> 00:57:59,620
Wait till you've been here
as long as Brooks.

801
00:57:59,860 --> 00:58:01,340
Goddamn right.

802
00:58:03,780 --> 00:58:05,660
They send you here for life...

803
00:58:06,300 --> 00:58:08,540
...that's exactly what they take.

804
00:58:10,220 --> 00:58:12,100
Part that counts, anyway.

805
00:58:19,420 --> 00:58:22,260
I can't take care of you no more, Jake.

806
00:58:23,340 --> 00:58:24,940
You go on now.

807
00:58:26,140 --> 00:58:27,580
You're free.

808
00:58:28,820 --> 00:58:30,300
You're free.

809
00:58:48,540 --> 00:58:50,140
Good luck, Brooksie.

810
00:59:26,540 --> 00:59:27,980
Dear fellas:

811
00:59:28,260 --> 00:59:32,300
I can't believe how fast things move
on the outside.

812
00:59:33,540 --> 00:59:36,100
Watch it, old-timer!
Want to get killed?

813
00:59:37,300 --> 00:59:40,620
I saw an automobile once
when I was a kid...

814
00:59:41,220 --> 00:59:43,580
...but now they're everywhere.

815
00:59:47,100 --> 00:59:51,220
The world went and got itself
in a big damn hurry.

816
01:00:06,380 --> 01:00:10,020
The parole board
got me into this halfway house...

817
01:00:10,300 --> 01:00:11,900
...called "The Brewer"...

818
01:00:12,060 --> 01:00:13,180
...and a job...

819
01:00:13,420 --> 01:00:16,260
...bagging groceries at the Food-Way.

820
01:00:17,700 --> 01:00:20,060
It's hard work and I try to keep up...

821
01:00:20,260 --> 01:00:22,500
...but my hands hurt most of the time.

822
01:00:22,820 --> 01:00:24,700
Make sure your man double-bags.

823
01:00:24,900 --> 01:00:26,860
Last time, the bottom near came out.

824
01:00:27,500 --> 01:00:30,300
Make sure you double-bag
like the lady says. Understand?

825
01:00:30,500 --> 01:00:31,780
Yes, sir. Surely will.

826
01:00:31,980 --> 01:00:35,380
I don't think the store manager
likes me very much.

827
01:00:38,260 --> 01:00:42,380
Sometimes after work,
I go to the park and feed the birds.

828
01:00:42,820 --> 01:00:44,260
I keep thinking...

829
01:00:44,500 --> 01:00:47,660
...Jake might just show up
and say hello.

830
01:00:48,260 --> 01:00:50,180
But he never does.

831
01:00:51,300 --> 01:00:55,980
I hope, wherever he is, he's doing okay
and making new friends.

832
01:00:59,460 --> 01:01:02,060
I have trouble sleeping at night.

833
01:01:02,380 --> 01:01:05,500
I have bad dreams like I'm falling.

834
01:01:05,740 --> 01:01:07,900
I wake up scared.

835
01:01:08,100 --> 01:01:12,140
Sometimes it takes me a while
to remember where I am.

836
01:01:13,620 --> 01:01:18,300
Maybe I should get a gun and rob
the Food-Way so they'd send me home.

837
01:01:18,580 --> 01:01:22,740
I could shoot the manager while
I was at it. Sort of like a bonus.

838
01:01:24,340 --> 01:01:28,180
I guess I'm too old
for that sort of nonsense anymore.

839
01:01:28,420 --> 01:01:30,060
I don't like it here.

840
01:01:30,260 --> 01:01:34,100
I'm tired of being afraid all the time.
I've decided...

841
01:01:34,900 --> 01:01:36,500
...not to stay.

842
01:01:46,980 --> 01:01:49,420
I doubt they'll kick up any fuss...

843
01:01:49,620 --> 01:01:52,980
...not for an old crook like me.

844
01:02:52,900 --> 01:02:56,980
"l doubt they'll kick up any fuss,
not for an old crook like me.

845
01:02:57,980 --> 01:03:01,660
P.S. Tell Heywood I'm sorry
I put a knife to his throat.

846
01:03:01,860 --> 01:03:04,100
No hard feelings. Brooks."

847
01:03:14,140 --> 01:03:16,020
He should have died in here.

848
01:03:21,340 --> 01:03:22,700
What the fuck have you done?

849
01:03:22,900 --> 01:03:25,420
It's a goddamn mess,
I'll tell you that.

850
01:03:30,740 --> 01:03:34,300
-What's all this?
-You tell me. They're addressed to you.

851
01:03:35,540 --> 01:03:36,820
Take it.

852
01:03:45,020 --> 01:03:46,460
"Dear Mr. Dufresne:

853
01:03:47,540 --> 01:03:49,420
In response to your inquiries...

854
01:03:49,620 --> 01:03:53,740
...the state has allocated the enclosed
funds for your library project."

855
01:03:54,460 --> 01:03:56,220
This is $200.

856
01:03:56,420 --> 01:04:00,260
"In addition, the library district
has generously responded...

857
01:04:00,460 --> 01:04:02,900
...with a donation of used books
and sundries.

858
01:04:03,100 --> 01:04:07,060
We trust this will fill your needs.
We now consider the matter closed.

859
01:04:07,260 --> 01:04:08,980
Please stop sending us letters."

860
01:04:09,220 --> 01:04:11,740
Clear all this out
before the warden gets back.

861
01:04:11,980 --> 01:04:13,100
Yes, sir.

862
01:04:17,220 --> 01:04:18,300
Good for you, Andy.

863
01:04:21,180 --> 01:04:22,260
Wow!

864
01:04:23,420 --> 01:04:25,260
It only took six years.

865
01:04:26,780 --> 01:04:29,420
From now on, I'll write two
letters a week instead of one.

866
01:04:29,580 --> 01:04:32,780
I believe you're crazy enough.
Get this stuff out...

867
01:04:33,060 --> 01:04:33,860
...like he said.

868
01:04:34,060 --> 01:04:35,380
I've got to pinch a loaf.

869
01:04:35,580 --> 01:04:37,020
When I come back...

870
01:04:37,180 --> 01:04:38,900
...this is all gone, all right?

871
01:05:25,660 --> 01:05:26,980
Do you hear that?

872
01:06:32,900 --> 01:06:34,020
Dufresne!

873
01:06:36,460 --> 01:06:37,900
Andy, let me out!

874
01:06:44,500 --> 01:06:49,220
I have no idea to this day what those
two Italian ladies were singing about.

875
01:06:49,540 --> 01:06:51,700
Truth is, I don't want to know.

876
01:06:51,900 --> 01:06:54,260
Some things are best left unsaid.

877
01:06:57,700 --> 01:07:00,300
I like to think it was something
so beautiful...

878
01:07:00,500 --> 01:07:02,540
...it can't be expressed in words...

879
01:07:02,740 --> 01:07:05,540
...and makes your heart ache
because of it.

880
01:07:07,140 --> 01:07:09,540
I tell you, those voices soared...

881
01:07:09,780 --> 01:07:13,900
...higher and farther than anybody
in a gray place dares to dream.

882
01:07:14,100 --> 01:07:17,340
It was like a beautiful bird
flapped into our drab cage...

883
01:07:17,540 --> 01:07:20,180
...and made those walls dissolve away.

884
01:07:20,620 --> 01:07:22,740
And for the briefest of moments...

885
01:07:22,900 --> 01:07:25,780
...every last man at Shawshank
felt free.

886
01:07:28,260 --> 01:07:30,820
It pissed the warden off
something awful.

887
01:07:32,060 --> 01:07:33,020
Open the door.

888
01:07:35,820 --> 01:07:37,500
Open it up!

889
01:07:38,740 --> 01:07:41,380
Dufresne, open this door!

890
01:07:42,660 --> 01:07:43,780
Turn that off!

891
01:07:50,580 --> 01:07:52,900
I am warning you. Turn that off!

892
01:08:09,940 --> 01:08:11,420
You're mine now.

893
01:08:18,540 --> 01:08:21,660
Andy got two weeks in the hole
for that little stunt.

894
01:08:21,820 --> 01:08:23,380
On your feet.

895
01:08:24,500 --> 01:08:26,780
-Hey, look who's here.
-Maestro!

896
01:08:28,460 --> 01:08:31,980
You couldn't play something good, huh?
Like Hank Williams?

897
01:08:32,300 --> 01:08:34,980
They broke the door down
before I could take requests.

898
01:08:35,180 --> 01:08:38,180
-Was it worth two weeks?
-Easiest time I ever did.

899
01:08:38,380 --> 01:08:42,380
-No such thing as easy time in the hole.
-A week in the hole is like a year.

900
01:08:42,620 --> 01:08:45,780
-Damn straight.
-I had Mr. Mozart to keep me company.

901
01:08:45,980 --> 01:08:48,820
So they let you tote
that record player down there, huh?

902
01:08:51,140 --> 01:08:52,460
It was in here.

903
01:08:53,260 --> 01:08:54,460
In here.

904
01:08:55,540 --> 01:08:57,540
That's the beauty of music. They...

905
01:08:57,740 --> 01:08:59,980
...can't get that from you.

906
01:09:03,380 --> 01:09:05,660
Haven't you ever felt
that way about music?

907
01:09:07,380 --> 01:09:10,380
Well, I played a mean harmonica
as a younger man.

908
01:09:11,380 --> 01:09:13,020
Lost interest in it, though.

909
01:09:13,220 --> 01:09:14,740
Didn't make much sense in here.

910
01:09:15,060 --> 01:09:16,980
Here's where it makes the most sense.

911
01:09:17,500 --> 01:09:19,460
You need it so you don't forget.

912
01:09:20,020 --> 01:09:21,180
Forget?

913
01:09:21,540 --> 01:09:24,500
Forget that there are...

914
01:09:24,700 --> 01:09:26,060
...places...

915
01:09:26,540 --> 01:09:30,220
...in the world
that aren't made out of stone.

916
01:09:31,180 --> 01:09:32,620
There's something...

917
01:09:32,940 --> 01:09:34,300
...inside...

918
01:09:34,540 --> 01:09:36,460
...that they can't get to...

919
01:09:36,660 --> 01:09:37,940
...that they can't touch.

920
01:09:38,460 --> 01:09:39,820
That's yours.

921
01:09:41,300 --> 01:09:42,820
What are you talking about?

922
01:09:43,820 --> 01:09:45,020
Hope.

923
01:09:46,060 --> 01:09:47,300
Hope.

924
01:09:49,180 --> 01:09:51,060
Let me tell you something, my friend.

925
01:09:51,860 --> 01:09:54,060
Hope is a dangerous thing.

926
01:09:55,240 --> 01:09:57,480
Hope can drive a man insane.

927
01:09:58,200 --> 01:10:00,200
It's got no use on the inside.

928
01:10:00,440 --> 01:10:02,520
You'd better get used to that idea.

929
01:10:04,920 --> 01:10:06,360
Like Brooks did?

930
01:10:30,720 --> 01:10:31,640
Sit down.

931
01:10:36,760 --> 01:10:39,960
Says here that you've served
30 years of a life sentence.

932
01:10:41,080 --> 01:10:43,040
You feel you've been rehabilitated?

933
01:10:43,240 --> 01:10:44,400
Oh, yes, sir.

934
01:10:45,640 --> 01:10:46,960
Without a doubt.

935
01:10:48,040 --> 01:10:50,360
I can honestly say I'm a changed man.

936
01:10:52,280 --> 01:10:54,120
No danger to society here.

937
01:10:54,640 --> 01:10:56,120
God's honest truth.

938
01:10:58,560 --> 01:11:00,600
Absolutely rehabilitated.

939
01:11:10,200 --> 01:11:11,440
Thirty years.

940
01:11:13,320 --> 01:11:15,160
Jesus, when you say it like that....

941
01:11:16,000 --> 01:11:17,720
You wonder where it went.

942
01:11:20,040 --> 01:11:22,120
I wonder where 1 0 years went.

943
01:11:26,920 --> 01:11:27,920
Here.

944
01:11:28,320 --> 01:11:30,960
A little parole rejection present.

945
01:11:32,160 --> 01:11:33,800
Go ahead and open it.

946
01:11:34,840 --> 01:11:36,760
Went through one of your competitors.

947
01:11:37,000 --> 01:11:40,000
I hope you don't mind.
I wanted it to be a surprise.

948
01:11:49,640 --> 01:11:51,040
It's very pretty.

949
01:11:52,680 --> 01:11:53,840
Thank you.

950
01:11:56,320 --> 01:11:57,720
You going to play it?

951
01:12:02,120 --> 01:12:03,320
No.

952
01:12:06,760 --> 01:12:08,120
Not right now.

953
01:12:25,080 --> 01:12:26,160
Roll in!

954
01:13:00,880 --> 01:13:02,040
Lights out!

955
01:13:35,240 --> 01:13:37,280
Andy was as good as his word.

956
01:13:37,640 --> 01:13:40,280
He wrote two letters a week
instead of one.

957
01:13:42,240 --> 01:13:46,200
In 1959, the state senate
finally clued in to the fact...

958
01:13:46,440 --> 01:13:49,440
...they couldn't buy him off
with just a $200 check.

959
01:13:49,600 --> 01:13:53,760
Appropriations Committee
voted an annual payment of $500...

960
01:13:53,960 --> 01:13:55,760
...just to shut him up.

961
01:13:55,960 --> 01:13:58,840
And you'd be amazed how far
Andy could stretch it.

962
01:13:59,040 --> 01:14:01,840
He made deals with book clubs,
charity groups.

963
01:14:02,040 --> 01:14:04,680
He bought remaindered books
by the pound....

964
01:14:05,200 --> 01:14:06,640
Treasure Island.

965
01:14:07,160 --> 01:14:08,440
Robert Louis--

966
01:14:08,640 --> 01:14:09,600
Stevenson.

967
01:14:09,840 --> 01:14:11,160
Fiction, adventure.

968
01:14:13,600 --> 01:14:14,600
What's next?

969
01:14:14,800 --> 01:14:17,720
I got here Auto Repair...

970
01:14:18,440 --> 01:14:19,560
...and Soap Carving.

971
01:14:19,720 --> 01:14:22,840
Trade skills and hobbies.
Under "Educational," behind you.

972
01:14:23,040 --> 01:14:24,840
Count of Monte Crisco.

973
01:14:25,280 --> 01:14:27,480
That's "Cristo," you dumb shit.

974
01:14:28,560 --> 01:14:29,480
By Alexandree...

975
01:14:29,920 --> 01:14:31,160
...Dum-ass.

976
01:14:31,480 --> 01:14:32,480
Dumb ass.

977
01:14:34,680 --> 01:14:35,680
Dumb ass?

978
01:14:38,480 --> 01:14:40,360
Dumas. Know what that's about?

979
01:14:42,560 --> 01:14:44,440
You'd like it.
It's about a prison break.

980
01:14:44,640 --> 01:14:48,400
We ought to file that
under "Educational" too, oughtn't we?

981
01:14:49,240 --> 01:14:53,160
The rest of us did our best
to pitch in when and where we could.

982
01:14:53,680 --> 01:14:55,360
By the year Kennedy was shot...

983
01:14:55,600 --> 01:14:59,920
...Andy had transformed a storage room
smelling of turpentine...

984
01:15:00,200 --> 01:15:03,200
...into the best prison library
in New England...

985
01:15:03,880 --> 01:15:06,680
...complete with a fine selection
of Hank Williams.

986
01:15:13,760 --> 01:15:15,640
That was also when Warden Norton...

987
01:15:15,800 --> 01:15:18,600
...instituted his famous
"Inside Out" program.

988
01:15:19,080 --> 01:15:21,040
You may remember reading about it.

989
01:15:21,280 --> 01:15:24,240
It made the papers
and got his picture in Look magazine.

990
01:15:24,440 --> 01:15:25,680
It's no free ride...

991
01:15:25,880 --> 01:15:28,960
..but rather a genuine
progressive advance...

992
01:15:29,160 --> 01:15:31,600
...in corrections and rehabilitation.

993
01:15:31,880 --> 01:15:34,320
Our inmates, properly supervised...

994
01:15:34,520 --> 01:15:37,040
...will be put to work
outside these walls...

995
01:15:37,280 --> 01:15:40,680
...performing all manner
of public service.

996
01:15:40,960 --> 01:15:43,040
These men can learn the value...

997
01:15:43,240 --> 01:15:46,880
...of an honest day's labor and
provide a service to the community...

998
01:15:47,120 --> 01:15:51,600
...at a bare minimum of expense
to Mr. and Mrs. John Q. Taxpayer.

999
01:15:52,040 --> 01:15:54,240
Of course he didn't tell the press...

1000
01:15:54,440 --> 01:15:57,800
...that "bare minimum of expense"
is a fairly loose term.

1001
01:15:57,960 --> 01:16:00,880
There are 100 different ways
to skim off the top.

1002
01:16:01,080 --> 01:16:03,480
Men, materials, you name it.

1003
01:16:03,800 --> 01:16:06,560
And oh, my Lord,
how the money rolled in!

1004
01:16:06,800 --> 01:16:09,200
At this rate,
you'll put me out of business.

1005
01:16:09,400 --> 01:16:13,680
With this pool of slave labor,
you can underbid any contractor in town.

1006
01:16:14,200 --> 01:16:17,040
We're providing
a valuable community service.

1007
01:16:17,240 --> 01:16:20,760
That's fine for the papers,
but I've got a family to feed.

1008
01:16:23,320 --> 01:16:24,800
We go back a long way.

1009
01:16:26,040 --> 01:16:30,760
I need this highway contract. I don't
get it and I go under. That's a fact.

1010
01:16:31,640 --> 01:16:33,400
You have some of this fine pie...

1011
01:16:33,600 --> 01:16:36,800
...my missus made for you.
You think about that.

1012
01:16:44,760 --> 01:16:47,320
I wouldn't worry too much
about this contract.

1013
01:16:47,560 --> 01:16:50,480
I already got my boys
committed elsewhere.

1014
01:16:52,360 --> 01:16:55,320
You be sure and thank Maisie
for this fine pie.

1015
01:16:56,360 --> 01:16:58,480
And behind every shady deal...

1016
01:16:58,800 --> 01:17:01,320
...behind every dollar earned...

1017
01:17:01,600 --> 01:17:04,480
...there was Andy, keeping the books.

1018
01:17:04,880 --> 01:17:06,120
Two deposits.

1019
01:17:06,320 --> 01:17:10,280
Maine National and New England First.
Night drops as always, sir.

1020
01:17:39,240 --> 01:17:43,440
Get my stuff to the laundry. Two suits
for dry-clean and a bag of whatnot.

1021
01:17:43,840 --> 01:17:47,280
If they over-starch my shirts again,
they'll hear from me.

1022
01:17:47,480 --> 01:17:48,720
