1269
01:31:19,120 --> 01:31:21,400
Will you throw that away, please?

1270
01:31:26,840 --> 01:31:28,480
Well, shit.

1271
01:31:40,640 --> 01:31:43,320
The kid passed. C + average.

1272
01:31:43,520 --> 01:31:45,520
Thought you'd like to know.

1273
01:32:01,080 --> 01:32:02,520
Warden wants to talk.

1274
01:32:15,680 --> 01:32:16,680
Out here?

1275
01:32:16,880 --> 01:32:19,040
That's what the man said.

1276
01:32:34,480 --> 01:32:35,440
Warden?

1277
01:32:45,040 --> 01:32:48,960
I'm asking you to keep this conversation
just between us.

1278
01:32:50,400 --> 01:32:52,560
I feel awkward enough as it is.

1279
01:33:10,280 --> 01:33:12,240
We got a situation here.

1280
01:33:13,080 --> 01:33:15,080
I think you can appreciate that.

1281
01:33:15,280 --> 01:33:16,480
Yes, sir.

1282
01:33:16,720 --> 01:33:18,080
I sure can.

1283
01:33:18,360 --> 01:33:22,200
I tell you, son, this thing really
came along and knocked my wind out.

1284
01:33:23,600 --> 01:33:26,040
It's got me up nights.
That's the truth.

1285
01:33:28,240 --> 01:33:30,000
The right thing to do...

1286
01:33:31,600 --> 01:33:35,200
...sometimes it's hard to know
what that is.

1287
01:33:36,160 --> 01:33:37,520
Do you understand?

1288
01:33:39,760 --> 01:33:41,280
I need your help, son.

1289
01:33:42,680 --> 01:33:44,720
If I'm going to move on this...

1290
01:33:45,040 --> 01:33:48,080
...there can't be
the least little shred of doubt.

1291
01:33:48,800 --> 01:33:49,800
I have to know...

1292
01:33:50,040 --> 01:33:52,520
...if what you told Dufresne
was the truth.

1293
01:33:52,720 --> 01:33:53,840
Yes, sir.

1294
01:33:54,040 --> 01:33:55,200
Absolutely.

1295
01:33:55,680 --> 01:33:58,560
Would you be willing to swear
before a judge and jury...

1296
01:33:58,720 --> 01:34:00,640
...with your hand on the Good Book...

1297
01:34:00,840 --> 01:34:03,400
...and take an oath
before Almighty God himself?

1298
01:34:03,600 --> 01:34:05,320
Just give me that chance.

1299
01:34:09,440 --> 01:34:10,720
That's what I thought.

1300
01:34:55,840 --> 01:34:57,720
I'm sure by now you've heard.

1301
01:34:59,400 --> 01:35:00,400
Terrible thing.

1302
01:35:01,920 --> 01:35:03,320
A man that young...

1303
01:35:03,640 --> 01:35:06,160
...less than a year to go,
trying to escape.

1304
01:35:06,640 --> 01:35:09,040
Broke Captain Hadley's heart
to shoot him.

1305
01:35:09,760 --> 01:35:11,200
Truly, it did.

1306
01:35:14,080 --> 01:35:16,440
We just have to put it behind us.

1307
01:35:18,040 --> 01:35:19,200
Move on.

1308
01:35:20,720 --> 01:35:22,160
I'm done.

1309
01:35:23,400 --> 01:35:24,960
Everything stops.

1310
01:35:26,880 --> 01:35:29,120
Get someone else to run your scams.

1311
01:35:30,360 --> 01:35:32,080
Nothing stops.

1312
01:35:33,360 --> 01:35:34,480
Nothing.

1313
01:35:37,760 --> 01:35:40,760
Or you will do
the hardest time there is.

1314
01:35:41,120 --> 01:35:43,320
No more protection from the guards.

1315
01:35:43,560 --> 01:35:48,280
I'll pull you out of that 1 -bunk Hilton
and cast you down with the sodomites.

1316
01:35:49,600 --> 01:35:51,960
You'll think you've been
fucked by a train.

1317
01:35:53,280 --> 01:35:54,720
And the library?

1318
01:35:55,360 --> 01:35:56,320
Gone.

1319
01:35:56,880 --> 01:35:59,360
Sealed off, brick by brick.

1320
01:35:59,800 --> 01:36:02,360
We'll have us a little
book barbecue in the yard.

1321
01:36:02,560 --> 01:36:04,600
They'll see the flames for miles.

1322
01:36:04,800 --> 01:36:07,520
We'll dance around it like wild Injuns.

1323
01:36:08,760 --> 01:36:11,600
You understand me? Catching my drift?

1324
01:36:15,200 --> 01:36:17,000
Or am I being obtuse?

1325
01:36:28,280 --> 01:36:30,800
Give him another month
to think about it.

1326
01:37:15,640 --> 01:37:18,560
My wife used to say
I'm a hard man to know.

1327
01:37:19,360 --> 01:37:21,080
Like a closed book.

1328
01:37:21,920 --> 01:37:23,800
Complained about it all the time.

1329
01:37:24,760 --> 01:37:26,240
She was beautiful.

1330
01:37:28,520 --> 01:37:30,000
God, I loved her.

1331
01:37:33,560 --> 01:37:35,720
I didn't know how
to show it, that's all.

1332
01:37:38,320 --> 01:37:39,920
I killed her, Red.

1333
01:37:41,720 --> 01:37:43,480
I didn't pull the trigger...

1334
01:37:44,840 --> 01:37:46,480
...but I drove her away.

1335
01:37:47,960 --> 01:37:50,520
That's why she died, because of me...

1336
01:37:50,720 --> 01:37:52,000
...the way I am.

1337
01:38:00,680 --> 01:38:02,400
That don't make you a murderer.

1338
01:38:05,680 --> 01:38:07,360
Bad husband, maybe.

1339
01:38:10,840 --> 01:38:13,960
Feel bad about it if you want,
but you didn't pull the trigger.

1340
01:38:14,200 --> 01:38:15,440
No, I didn't.

1341
01:38:15,840 --> 01:38:17,680
Somebody else did.

1342
01:38:18,880 --> 01:38:20,920
And I wound up in here.

1343
01:38:23,280 --> 01:38:24,760
Bad luck, I guess.

1344
01:38:29,800 --> 01:38:31,200
It floats around.

1345
01:38:32,160 --> 01:38:34,280
It's got to land on somebody.

1346
01:38:35,160 --> 01:38:36,960
It was my turn, that's all.

1347
01:38:37,680 --> 01:38:40,320
I was in the path of the tornado.

1348
01:38:46,040 --> 01:38:49,840
I just didn't expect the storm
would last as long as it has.

1349
01:38:53,960 --> 01:38:55,600
Think you'll ever get out of here?

1350
01:38:56,800 --> 01:38:57,760
Me?

1351
01:39:00,640 --> 01:39:01,600
Yeah.

1352
01:39:02,880 --> 01:39:05,080
One day, when I got
a long, white beard...

1353
01:39:05,280 --> 01:39:08,320
...and two or three marbles
rolling around upstairs.

1354
01:39:10,280 --> 01:39:11,840
I tell you where I'd go.

1355
01:39:13,280 --> 01:39:14,840
Zihuatanejo.

1356
01:39:15,680 --> 01:39:16,840
Say what?

1357
01:39:17,120 --> 01:39:18,880
Zihuatanejo.

1358
01:39:19,800 --> 01:39:21,360
It's in Mexico.

1359
01:39:22,720 --> 01:39:24,720
A little place on the Pacific Ocean.

1360
01:39:25,800 --> 01:39:28,480
You know what the Mexicans say
about the Pacific?

1361
01:39:30,240 --> 01:39:32,120
They say it has no memory.

1362
01:39:34,040 --> 01:39:36,600
That's where I want to live
the rest of my life.

1363
01:39:38,160 --> 01:39:40,560
A warm place with no memory.

1364
01:39:43,680 --> 01:39:45,520
Open up a little hotel...

1365
01:39:47,160 --> 01:39:48,600
...right on the beach.

1366
01:39:49,160 --> 01:39:51,280
Buy some worthless old boat...

1367
01:39:51,800 --> 01:39:53,360
...and fix it up new.

1368
01:39:56,000 --> 01:39:57,200
Take my guests out...

1369
01:39:58,000 --> 01:39:59,280
...charter fishing.

1370
01:40:03,000 --> 01:40:04,640
Zihuatanejo.

1371
01:40:08,040 --> 01:40:11,720
In a place like that, I could use
a man that knows how to get things.

1372
01:40:18,000 --> 01:40:20,760
I don't think I could make it
on the outside.

1373
01:40:27,160 --> 01:40:29,120
I been in here most of my life.

1374
01:40:30,480 --> 01:40:32,160
I'm an institutional man now.

1375
01:40:33,040 --> 01:40:34,720
Just like Brooks was.

1376
01:40:36,120 --> 01:40:37,720
You underestimate yourself.

1377
01:40:38,320 --> 01:40:39,800
I don't think so.

1378
01:40:43,520 --> 01:40:47,280
In here I'm the guy who can get things
for you, sure, but...

1379
01:40:48,000 --> 01:40:50,440
...outside all you need
is the Yellow Pages.

1380
01:40:50,680 --> 01:40:52,760
Hell, I wouldn't know
where to begin.

1381
01:40:54,840 --> 01:40:56,400
Pacific Ocean?

1382
01:40:56,800 --> 01:40:58,000
Shit.

1383
01:40:58,320 --> 01:41:00,440
Scare me to death,
something that big.

1384
01:41:00,640 --> 01:41:01,880
Not me.

1385
01:41:03,040 --> 01:41:05,720
I didn't shoot my wife,
and I didn't shoot her lover.

1386
01:41:07,360 --> 01:41:10,480
Whatever mistakes I made,
I've paid for them and then some.

1387
01:41:11,440 --> 01:41:12,880
That hotel, that boat....

1388
01:41:14,600 --> 01:41:16,720
I don't think that's too much to ask.

1389
01:41:21,440 --> 01:41:23,760
You shouldn't be doing this to yourself.

1390
01:41:23,960 --> 01:41:25,920
This is just shitty pipe dreams.

1391
01:41:26,360 --> 01:41:28,680
Mexico is way down there
and you're in here...

1392
01:41:28,920 --> 01:41:30,360
...and that's the way it is.

1393
01:41:30,720 --> 01:41:33,440
Yeah, right.
That's the way it is.

1394
01:41:34,880 --> 01:41:37,200
It's down there and I'm in here.

1395
01:41:39,640 --> 01:41:42,280
I guess it comes down
to a simple choice.

1396
01:41:45,080 --> 01:41:46,480
Get busy living...

1397
01:41:47,840 --> 01:41:49,760
...or get busy dying.

1398
01:42:01,360 --> 01:42:03,960
If you ever get out of here,
do me a favor.

1399
01:42:04,200 --> 01:42:06,360
Sure, Andy. Anything.

1400
01:42:08,160 --> 01:42:11,880
There's a big hayfield up near Buxton.
You know where Buxton is?

1401
01:42:13,240 --> 01:42:16,280
-A lot of hayfields up there.
-One in particular.

1402
01:42:16,480 --> 01:42:20,240
It's got a long rock wall
with a big oak tree at the north end.

1403
01:42:20,440 --> 01:42:23,200
It's like something
out of a Robert Frost poem.

1404
01:42:24,080 --> 01:42:26,480
It's where I asked my wife to marry me.

1405
01:42:27,840 --> 01:42:29,840
We went there for a picnic...

1406
01:42:30,240 --> 01:42:32,240
...and made love under that oak...

1407
01:42:32,880 --> 01:42:35,040
...and I asked and she said yes.

1408
01:42:38,880 --> 01:42:40,640
Promise me, Red.

1409
01:42:41,440 --> 01:42:43,000
If you ever get out...

1410
01:42:43,200 --> 01:42:44,640
...find that spot.

1411
01:42:45,760 --> 01:42:50,400
At the base of that wall, there's a rock
that has no earthly business in Maine.

1412
01:42:51,480 --> 01:42:54,400
Piece of black, volcanic glass.

1413
01:42:56,960 --> 01:42:59,520
Something's buried under it
I want you to have.

1414
01:43:00,240 --> 01:43:01,440
What, Andy?

1415
01:43:01,880 --> 01:43:03,520
What's buried under there?

1416
01:43:05,040 --> 01:43:06,840
You'll have to pry it up...

1417
01:43:07,040 --> 01:43:08,240
...to see.

1418
01:43:13,880 --> 01:43:15,800
No, I'm telling you. The guy is....

1419
01:43:16,400 --> 01:43:18,080
He's talking funny.

1420
01:43:19,120 --> 01:43:20,760
I'm really worried about him.

1421
01:43:21,160 --> 01:43:22,520
Let's keep an eye on him.

1422
01:43:22,720 --> 01:43:25,840
That's fine during the day,
but at night he's all alone.

1423
01:43:27,200 --> 01:43:28,280
Oh, Lord.

1424
01:43:29,600 --> 01:43:30,400
What?

1425
01:43:31,840 --> 01:43:34,520
Andy come down
to the loading dock today.

1426
01:43:34,680 --> 01:43:36,680
He asked me for a length of rope.

1427
01:43:36,880 --> 01:43:37,680
Rope?

1428
01:43:37,880 --> 01:43:39,480
Six feet long.

1429
01:43:39,720 --> 01:43:41,040
And you gave it to him.

1430
01:43:41,840 --> 01:43:43,560
Sure. Why wouldn't l?

1431
01:43:43,800 --> 01:43:45,240
Jesus! Heywood.

1432
01:43:45,880 --> 01:43:47,760
How was I supposed to know?

1433
01:43:47,920 --> 01:43:49,440
Remember Brooks Hatlen?

1434
01:43:51,360 --> 01:43:53,240
Andy would never do that.

1435
01:43:53,800 --> 01:43:54,800
Never.

1436
01:43:56,800 --> 01:43:58,080
I don't know.

1437
01:44:00,800 --> 01:44:02,760
Every man has his breaking point.

1438
01:44:05,000 --> 01:44:07,160
Lickety-split.
Want to get home.

1439
01:44:07,480 --> 01:44:09,160
Just about finished, sir.

1440
01:44:25,560 --> 01:44:27,160
Three deposits tonight.

1441
01:44:34,760 --> 01:44:36,600
Get my stuff down to the laundry.

1442
01:44:36,800 --> 01:44:38,360
And shine my shoes.

1443
01:44:38,560 --> 01:44:41,360
-I want them looking like mirrors.
-Yes, sir.

1444
01:44:46,680 --> 01:44:48,040
It's good having you back.

1445
01:44:48,960 --> 01:44:50,720
Place wasn't the same without you.

1446
01:45:35,680 --> 01:45:36,720
Lights out!

1447
01:46:08,240 --> 01:46:10,640
I've had some long nights in stir.

1448
01:46:11,160 --> 01:46:13,720
Alone in the dark
with nothing but your thoughts...

1449
01:46:13,920 --> 01:46:16,480
...time can draw out like a blade.

1450
01:46:21,600 --> 01:46:24,440
That was the longest night of my life.

1451
01:46:39,680 --> 01:46:40,800
Give me a count!

1452
01:46:45,120 --> 01:46:47,840
Tier 3 south, clear!

1453
01:46:50,840 --> 01:46:53,880
Man missing on tier 2, cell 245!

1454
01:46:54,080 --> 01:46:55,120
Dufresne!

1455
01:46:55,600 --> 01:46:57,920
Come out. You're holding up the show!

1456
01:47:00,960 --> 01:47:04,240
Don't make me come down
or I'll thump your skull for you!

1457
01:47:11,480 --> 01:47:15,160
Damn it, you're putting me behind!
I got a schedule to keep.

1458
01:47:15,360 --> 01:47:18,520
You'd better be sick or dead in there.
I shit you not!

1459
01:47:18,720 --> 01:47:20,000
You hear me?

1460
01:47:25,880 --> 01:47:27,880
Oh, my Holy God.

1461
01:47:44,160 --> 01:47:46,640
I want every man
on this cellblock questioned.

1462
01:47:47,040 --> 01:47:49,480
-Start with that friend of his.
-Who?

1463
01:47:51,960 --> 01:47:53,440
Open 237.

1464
01:47:56,840 --> 01:48:00,360
What do you mean, "He just wasn't here"?
Don't say that to me.

1465
01:48:01,200 --> 01:48:02,480
Don't tell me that again.

1466
01:48:02,640 --> 01:48:03,640
But sir, he wasn't.

1467
01:48:03,880 --> 01:48:07,200
I can see that, Haig!
Think I'm blind?

1468
01:48:07,840 --> 01:48:09,160
Is that what you're saying?

1469
01:48:09,360 --> 01:48:11,920
-Am I blind, Haig?
-No, sir!

1470
01:48:12,800 --> 01:48:15,200
What about you. You blind?

1471
01:48:15,680 --> 01:48:18,120
-Tell me what this is.
-Last night's count.

1472
01:48:18,360 --> 01:48:21,480
You see Dufresne's name there?
I sure do. Right there.

1473
01:48:21,680 --> 01:48:23,000
"Dufresne."

1474
01:48:24,560 --> 01:48:25,960
He was in his cell...

1475
01:48:26,200 --> 01:48:27,120
...at lights out.

1476
01:48:27,320 --> 01:48:29,520
Reasonable he'd be here in the morning.

1477
01:48:30,520 --> 01:48:32,040
I want him found.

1478
01:48:32,280 --> 01:48:35,560
Not tomorrow, not after breakfast. Now!

1479
01:48:35,800 --> 01:48:36,960
Yes, sir.

1480
01:48:37,920 --> 01:48:40,080
Let's go. Move your butts.

1481
01:48:43,360 --> 01:48:44,320
Stand.

1482
01:48:45,680 --> 01:48:46,680
Well?

1483
01:48:50,000 --> 01:48:50,960
Well, what?

1484
01:48:51,200 --> 01:48:54,480
I see you two all the time.
You're thick as thieves, you are.

1485
01:48:55,520 --> 01:48:56,920
He must have said something.

1486
01:48:57,680 --> 01:48:59,120
No, sir, Warden.

1487
01:48:59,480 --> 01:49:00,440
Not a word.

1488
01:49:02,200 --> 01:49:04,640
Lord, it's a miracle!

1489
01:49:05,240 --> 01:49:07,680
Man vanished like a fart in the wind.

1490
01:49:08,320 --> 01:49:09,440
Nothing left...

1491
01:49:10,240 --> 01:49:12,840
...but some damn rocks
on a windowsill.

1492
01:49:13,040 --> 01:49:15,640
And that cupcake on the wall.
Let's ask her.

1493
01:49:15,880 --> 01:49:17,560
Maybe she knows.

1494
01:49:17,800 --> 01:49:20,400
What say there, fuzzy-britches?
Feel like talking?

1495
01:49:21,800 --> 01:49:23,040
Guess not.

1496
01:49:23,600 --> 01:49:25,680
Why should she be any different?

1497
01:49:26,720 --> 01:49:28,320
This is a conspiracy.

1498
01:49:28,920 --> 01:49:30,680
That's what this is.

1499
01:49:31,280 --> 01:49:34,840
One big, damn conspiracy!

1500
01:49:35,120 --> 01:49:37,040
And everyone's in on it!

1501
01:49:37,640 --> 01:49:38,760
Including her!

1502
01:50:12,360 --> 01:50:13,960
In 1966...

1503
01:50:14,160 --> 01:50:16,480
...Andy Dufresne escaped...

1504
01:50:16,640 --> 01:50:18,160
...from Shawshank Prison.

1505
01:50:20,320 --> 01:50:22,800
All they found
was a muddy set of prison clothes...

1506
01:50:23,400 --> 01:50:24,880
...a bar of soap...

1507
01:50:25,040 --> 01:50:26,560
...and an old rock hammer...

1508
01:50:26,760 --> 01:50:29,120
...damn near worn down to the nub.

1509
01:50:33,440 --> 01:50:38,040
I had thought it'd take a man 600 years
to tunnel through the wall with it.

1510
01:50:38,640 --> 01:50:41,120
Old Andy did it in less than 20.

1511
01:50:58,680 --> 01:51:00,880
Oh, Andy loved geology.

1512
01:51:01,600 --> 01:51:04,640
I imagine it appealed to his
meticulous nature.

1513
01:51:05,080 --> 01:51:06,800
An ice age here...

1514
01:51:07,200 --> 01:51:09,640
...million years
of mountain building there.

1515
01:51:10,600 --> 01:51:13,320
Geology is the study
of pressure and time.

1516
01:51:14,120 --> 01:51:16,040
That's all it takes, really.

1517
01:51:16,720 --> 01:51:17,760
Pressure...

1518
01:51:18,400 --> 01:51:19,600
...and time.

1519
01:51:20,920 --> 01:51:22,880
That and a big goddamn poster.

1520
01:51:26,720 --> 01:51:27,640
Like I said...

1521
01:51:28,120 --> 01:51:31,960
...in prison, a man will do anything
to keep his mind occupied.

1522
01:51:34,640 --> 01:51:39,240
Seems Andy's favorite hobby was toting
his wall out into the exercise yard...

1523
01:51:39,800 --> 01:51:41,640
...a handful at a time.

1524
01:51:42,880 --> 01:51:44,840
I guess after Tommy was killed...

1525
01:51:45,040 --> 01:51:47,920
...Andy decided
he'd been here long enough.

1526
01:51:48,120 --> 01:51:50,560
Lickety-split.
I want to get home.

1527
01:51:51,240 --> 01:51:53,200
I'm just about finished, sir.

1528
01:52:13,760 --> 01:52:15,640
Three deposits tonight.

1529
01:52:22,680 --> 01:52:24,840
Andy did like he was told.

1530
01:52:25,040 --> 01:52:28,400
Buffed those shoes
to a high mirror-shine.

1531
01:52:31,920 --> 01:52:34,160
The guards simply didn't notice.

1532
01:52:34,440 --> 01:52:35,840
Neither did l.

1533
01:52:36,040 --> 01:52:37,480
I mean, seriously...

1534
01:52:37,720 --> 01:52:40,560
...how often do you really look
at a man's shoes?

1535
01:54:39,080 --> 01:54:42,120
Andy crawled to freedom
through 500 yards...

1536
01:54:42,360 --> 01:54:45,520
...of shit-smelling foulness
I can't even imagine.

1537
01:54:46,480 --> 01:54:48,720
Or maybe I just don't want to.

1538
01:54:52,960 --> 01:54:55,240
Five hundred yards.

1539
01:54:55,680 --> 01:54:58,640
That's the length
of five football fields.

1540
01:54:59,280 --> 01:55:01,720
Just shy of half a mile.

1541
01:55:54,680 --> 01:55:59,120
The next morning, right about the time
Raquel was spilling her secret...

1542
01:55:59,360 --> 01:56:02,080
...a man nobody ever
laid eyes on before...

1543
01:56:02,320 --> 01:56:04,840
...strolled into
the Maine National Bank.

1544
01:56:05,360 --> 01:56:08,400
Until that moment,
he didn't exist.

1545
01:56:08,960 --> 01:56:11,240
-Except on paper.
-May I help you?

1546
01:56:11,600 --> 01:56:13,440
He had all the proper ID...

1547
01:56:13,640 --> 01:56:17,200
...driver's license, birth certificate,
Social Security card....

1548
01:56:17,640 --> 01:56:20,040
And the signature
was a spot-on match.

1549
01:56:20,240 --> 01:56:23,240
I must say I'm sorry
to be losing your business.

1550
01:56:23,440 --> 01:56:25,080
I hope you'll enjoy living abroad.

1551
01:56:25,840 --> 01:56:26,880
Thank you.

1552
01:56:27,520 --> 01:56:28,640
I'm sure I will.

1553
01:56:29,520 --> 01:56:32,720
Here's your cashier's check, sir.
Will there be anything else?

1554
01:56:32,960 --> 01:56:33,880
Please.

1555
01:56:34,440 --> 01:56:36,800
Would you add this
to your outgoing mail?

1556
01:56:37,320 --> 01:56:38,480
I'd be happy to.

1557
01:56:40,200 --> 01:56:41,440
Good day, sir.

1558
01:56:42,360 --> 01:56:46,640
Mr. Stevens visited nearly a dozen banks
in the Portland area that morning.

1559
01:56:47,040 --> 01:56:48,600
All told, he blew town...

1560
01:56:48,800 --> 01:56:53,440
...with better than $370,000
of Warden Norton's money.

1561
01:56:54,120 --> 01:56:56,760
Severance pay for 19 years.

1562
01:57:03,720 --> 01:57:05,800
Good morning, Portland Daily Bugle.

1563
01:57:56,480 --> 01:57:59,320
Byron Hadley?
You have the right to remain silent.

1564
01:57:59,560 --> 01:58:03,840
If you give up this right, anything you
say can be held against you in court.

1565
01:58:04,240 --> 01:58:08,520
I wasn't there to see, but I hear
Byron Hadley sobbed like a girl...

1566
01:58:08,720 --> 01:58:10,160
...when they took him away.

1567
01:58:15,800 --> 01:58:19,040
Norton had no intention
of going that quietly.

1568
01:58:34,280 --> 01:58:35,040
Samuel Norton.

1569
01:58:35,840 --> 01:58:38,160
We have a warrant
for your arrest. Open up.

1570
01:58:42,720 --> 01:58:43,760
Open the door.

1571
01:58:44,280 --> 01:58:45,480
I'm not sure which key.

1572
01:58:55,240 --> 01:58:57,080
Make it easy on yourself, Norton!

1573
01:59:08,120 --> 01:59:11,440
I like to think the last thing
that went through his head...

1574
01:59:11,640 --> 01:59:13,160
...other than that bullet...

1575
01:59:13,360 --> 01:59:17,640
...was to wonder how the hell
Andy Dufresne ever got the best of him.

1576
01:59:20,040 --> 01:59:23,360
Not long after the warden
deprived us of his company...

1577
01:59:23,600 --> 01:59:25,560
...I got a postcard in the mail.

1578
01:59:27,000 --> 01:59:29,720
It was blank,
but the postmark said...

1579
01:59:29,920 --> 01:59:31,960
...Fort Hancock, Texas.

1580
01:59:32,480 --> 01:59:33,760
Fort Hancock...

1581
01:59:34,040 --> 01:59:35,680
...right on the border.

1582
01:59:36,080 --> 01:59:38,000
That's where Andy crossed.

1583
01:59:38,560 --> 01:59:42,520
When I picture him heading south
in his own car with the top down...

1584
01:59:42,840 --> 01:59:44,960
...it always makes me laugh.

1585
01:59:46,760 --> 01:59:48,240
Andy Dufresne...

1586
01:59:48,600 --> 01:59:50,560
...who crawled through
a river of shit...

1587
01:59:50,720 --> 01:59:53,040
...and came out clean
on the other side.

1588
01:59:53,840 --> 01:59:55,160
Andy Dufresne...

1589
01:59:55,960 --> 01:59:57,440
...headed for the Pacific.

1590
02:00:00,320 --> 02:00:02,400
Hadley's got him
by the throat, right?

1591
02:00:02,600 --> 02:00:06,240
He says, "l believe this boy's
about to have himself an accident."

1592
02:00:06,440 --> 02:00:09,200
Those of us who knew him best
talk about him often.

1593
02:00:09,840 --> 02:00:11,440
I swear, the stuff he pulled....

1594
02:00:11,640 --> 02:00:14,480
"My friends could use
a couple of beers."

1595
02:00:14,840 --> 02:00:16,400
And he got it!

1596
02:00:17,600 --> 02:00:19,880
Sometimes it makes me sad, though...

1597
02:00:20,160 --> 02:00:21,520
...Andy being gone.

1598
02:00:22,200 --> 02:00:26,200
I have to remind myself that
some birds aren't meant to be caged.

1599
02:00:26,600 --> 02:00:28,600
Their feathers are just too bright.

1600
02:00:30,240 --> 02:00:31,880
And when they fly away...

1601
02:00:32,320 --> 02:00:36,520
...the part of you that knows it was
a sin to lock them up does rejoice.

1602
02:00:37,560 --> 02:00:38,760
But still...

1603
02:00:39,240 --> 02:00:43,360
...the place you live in is that much
more drab and empty that they're gone.

1604
02:00:47,440 --> 02:00:49,680
I guess I just miss my friend.

1605
02:01:13,360 --> 02:01:14,280
Please sit down.

1606
02:01:19,880 --> 02:01:21,360
Ellis Boyd Redding...

1607
02:01:21,880 --> 02:01:25,040
...your files say you've served
40 years of a life sentence.

1608
02:01:25,800 --> 02:01:27,840
You feel you've been rehabilitated?

1609
02:01:29,640 --> 02:01:31,120
Rehabilitated?

1610
02:01:33,080 --> 02:01:34,920
Well, now, let me see.

1611
02:01:35,880 --> 02:01:38,120
I don't have any idea
what that means.

1612
02:01:40,160 --> 02:01:42,280
It means you're ready
to rejoin society--

1613
02:01:42,840 --> 02:01:45,080
I know what you think it means, sonny.

1614
02:01:47,160 --> 02:01:49,080
To me it's just a made-up word.

1615
02:01:50,360 --> 02:01:52,600
A politician's word so that...

1616
02:01:53,040 --> 02:01:56,400
...young fellas like yourself
can wear a suit and a tie...

1617
02:01:56,880 --> 02:01:58,400
...and have a job.

1618
02:02:00,280 --> 02:02:02,280
What do you really want to know?

1619
02:02:03,040 --> 02:02:04,920
Am I sorry for what I did?

1620
02:02:05,360 --> 02:02:06,440
Well, are you?

1621
02:02:08,280 --> 02:02:11,000
There's not a day goes by
I don't feel regret.

1622
02:02:12,320 --> 02:02:15,640
Not because I'm in here
or because you think I should.

1623
02:02:18,960 --> 02:02:21,400
I look back on the way I was then...

1624
02:02:23,480 --> 02:02:24,600
...a young...

1625
02:02:25,680 --> 02:02:29,000
...stupid kid who committed
that terrible crime.

1626
02:02:31,880 --> 02:02:33,560
I want to talk to him.

1627
02:02:35,400 --> 02:02:37,760
I want to try
and talk some sense to him.

1628
02:02:38,440 --> 02:02:40,320
Tell him the way things are.

1629
02:02:42,320 --> 02:02:43,720
But I can't.

1630
02:02:45,800 --> 02:02:47,720
That kid's long gone...

1631
02:02:48,880 --> 02:02:51,520
...and this old man is all that's left.

1632
02:02:52,880 --> 02:02:54,280
I got to live with that.

1633
02:02:55,600 --> 02:02:57,240
Rehabilitated?

1634
02:02:57,600 --> 02:02:59,360
It's just a bullshit word.

1635
02:03:00,240 --> 02:03:04,840
So you go on and stamp your forms,
sonny, and stop wasting my time.

1636
02:03:06,000 --> 02:03:08,200
Because to tell you the truth...

1637
02:03:08,520 --> 02:03:10,400
...I don't give a shit.

1638
02:04:33,440 --> 02:04:34,760
Here you go, miss.

1639
02:04:37,560 --> 02:04:38,560
Restroom break?

1640
02:04:44,120 --> 02:04:48,440
You don't need to ask me every time
you need to go take a piss. Just go.

1641
02:05:01,000 --> 02:05:03,920
Forty years I've been asking
permission to piss.

1642
02:05:04,720 --> 02:05:07,600
I can't squeeze a drop without say-so.

1643
02:05:10,960 --> 02:05:13,040
There's a harsh truth to face.

1644
02:05:14,640 --> 02:05:17,440
No way I'm going to make it
on the outside.

1645
02:05:24,960 --> 02:05:28,560
All I do anymore is think of ways
to break my parole...

1646
02:05:29,320 --> 02:05:31,680
...so maybe they'd send me back.

1647
02:05:36,680 --> 02:05:39,000
Terrible thing, to live in fear.

1648
02:05:39,880 --> 02:05:41,480
Brooks Hatlen knew it.

1649
02:05:41,680 --> 02:05:43,520
Knew it all too well.

1650
02:05:45,040 --> 02:05:48,320
All I want is to be back
where things make sense.

1651
02:05:48,720 --> 02:05:51,320
Where I won't have to be afraid
all the time.

1652
02:05:53,280 --> 02:05:55,560
Only one thing stops me.

1653
02:05:56,920 --> 02:05:59,240
A promise I made to Andy.

1654
02:06:18,920 --> 02:06:20,000
There it is.

1655
02:06:30,160 --> 02:06:31,760
Much obliged, sir.

1656
02:10:02,120 --> 02:10:03,320
Dear Red:

1657
02:10:03,560 --> 02:10:05,920
If you're reading this,
you've gotten out...

1658
02:10:06,080 --> 02:10:10,000
...and if you've come this far,
maybe you'd come a bit further.

1659
02:10:10,280 --> 02:10:12,640
You remember the name
of the town, don't you?

1660
02:10:14,840 --> 02:10:16,240
Zihuatanejo.

1661
02:10:17,880 --> 02:10:21,280
I could use a good man
to help me get my project on wheels.

1662
02:10:21,800 --> 02:10:25,160
I'll keep an eye out for you,
and the chessboard ready.

1663
02:10:25,960 --> 02:10:27,320
Remember, Red...

1664
02:10:27,600 --> 02:10:29,600
...hope is a good thing...

1665
02:10:29,840 --> 02:10:31,720
...maybe the best of things.

1666
02:10:31,960 --> 02:10:34,000
And no good thing ever dies.

1667
02:10:34,520 --> 02:10:37,280
I will be hoping
that this letter finds you...

1668
02:10:37,480 --> 02:10:39,120
...and finds you well.

1669
02:10:39,640 --> 02:10:40,760
Your friend...

1670
02:10:41,000 --> 02:10:42,120
...Andy.

1671
02:11:14,560 --> 02:11:16,200
"Get busy living...

1672
02:11:16,400 --> 02:11:18,240
...or get busy dying. "

1673
02:11:20,840 --> 02:11:22,880
That's goddamn right.

1674
02:11:27,920 --> 02:11:30,000
For the second time in my life...

1675
02:11:30,200 --> 02:11:32,680
...I'm guilty of committing a crime.

1676
02:11:33,720 --> 02:11:35,560
Parole violation.

1677
02:11:36,200 --> 02:11:39,680
Of course I doubt they'll toss up
any roadblocks for that.

1678
02:11:40,360 --> 02:11:42,320
Not for an old crook like me.

1679
02:11:42,480 --> 02:11:44,440
Fort Hancock, Texas, please.

1680
02:11:48,000 --> 02:11:52,520
I find I'm so excited I can barely
sit still or hold a thought in my head.

1681
02:11:52,920 --> 02:11:56,120
I think it's the excitement
only a free man can feel.

1682
02:11:56,320 --> 02:11:58,720
A free man at the start
of a long journey...

1683
02:11:58,920 --> 02:12:01,400
...whose conclusion is uncertain.

1684
02:12:04,280 --> 02:12:06,840
I hope I can make it across the border.

1685
02:12:08,280 --> 02:12:11,200
I hope to see my friend
and shake his hand.

1686
02:12:13,000 --> 02:12:16,880
I hope the Pacific is as blue
as it has been in my dreams.

1687
02:12:18,680 --> 02:12:19,800
I hope.

